y labor unions that actively discouraged the pursuit of political causes unrelated to their own economic interests. Drawing on a wealth of original data, Ahlquist and Levi show how activist organizations can profoundly transform the views of members about their political efficacy and the collective actions they are willing to contemplate. They find that leaders who ask for support of projects without obvious material benefits must first demonstrate their ability to deliver the goods and services members expect. These leaders must also build governance institutions that coordinate expectations about their objectives and the behavior of members. In the Interest of Others reveals how activist labor unions expand the community of fate and provoke preferences that transcend the private interests of individual members. Ahlquist and Levi then extend this logic to other membership organizations, including religious groups, political parties, and the state itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activity. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh  aILWU leaders.  aILWU members.  aInternational Brotherhood of Teamsters.  aInternational Longshore and Warehouse Union.  aInternational Longshoremen's Association.  aMaritime Union of Australia.  aWaterside Workers' Federation.  aactivist unions.  aaggregate behavior.  aaltruism.  abusiness unions.  acooperation.  aeconomic opportunities.  aeconomism.  aequilibrium selection.  aethnic divisions.  agovernance arrangements.  agovernance equilibrium.  agovernance.  aill-formed beliefs.  aindividual members.  aindustrial efficacy.  ainformation acquisition.  ainternal heterogeneity.  ainternational trade.  alabor organization.  alabor unions.  aleadership rents.  amembers.  ame